So that was the last bit of action from the first session. It will be England who will enjoy Lunch more. It was a session of two halves with the first half belonging to the side from the Caribbean while the second belonged to Broad and England. Join us for the second session and West Indies' reply.

They had England stuttering at 122/4 initially but then let that slip and when they had a chance to restrict the hosts under 300 they failed to do that as well. Kemar Roach was the pick of the bowlers and ended with a 4-fer. Gabriel and Chase had 2 wickets each while Holder finished with one. The extra spinner, Cornwall, who was picked for this game went wicketless. All-in-all Holder and his men will not be too pleased with their efforts, considering where they were at one stage.

They say if you bowl first and do not concede in excess of 400, you would be happy. But West Indies will be disappointed with their bowling effort. They were on top in the first 2 sessions of Day 1 but then let it slip away. They were then again in a strong position in the first hour of Day 2 but once again they let it loose and it backfired.

Buttler and Pope though found their groove and the pair added a 140-run stand. But the start of Day 2 saw Pope miss out on his century by 9 runs and wickets started to crumble from there on. The hosts slipped from 262/4 to 280/8 before Broad came to the party.

After being put into bat, England got off to a poor start losing Sibley early. They kept losing wickets regularly but Burns' fifty gave them some solidarity. After his dismissal, the hosts were reeling at 122/4 and it looked like they would struggle to get to 250. Add to the fact that Jos Buttler was in poor form and they had picked an extra bowler.

A blistering 62 from Stuart Broad has turned the tide in favour of England. When 300 looked tough, his knock has taken them past 350. The hosts would be reasonably happy with this total, given the reactions in their dressing room. It was a torrid opening hour but this second half has given them something to smile.

Hello and welcome to Day 2 of the third and final Test between England and West Indies. After enjoying much of Day 1, West Indies could not end the day on a high and are now on the back foot. England, on the other hand, are in a strong position with Buttler and Pope in the middle of a 136-run stand. The hosts would hope that the pair can carry on its good work and take the total in excess of 400.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

So that is it from Day 1 of this third and final Test between England and West Indies. The hosts look good and strong but West Indies will look to bounce back and have a fruitful morning on Day 2. The home side will once again look to get past 400 but the tourists know that this is the last recognized batting pair and will look to have an early breakthrough. The weather forecast for Day 2 is not too promising but let's hope we have some action. Join us on Saturday, 25th July for Day 2 of the deciding Test. The action starts at 1100 local (1000 GMT). Till then, take care and goodbye!

It started so brightly for the West Indies. Yes Gabriel's fitness was a concern after the opening half an hour but he recovered and the visitors were in command for the first two sessions. However, Pope and Buttler showed resilience and the disciplined bowling of Holder and his men could not beat the patience of the English pair. Roach and Chase were the two bowlers with the wickets with 2 and 1 each with the latter also contributing with a run out. Gabriel bowled his heart out but to no reward. Cornwall and Holder also had a non-fruitful day.

A very good day of Test cricket. After winning the toss and opting to bowl, West Indies started off well getting rid of last Test's centurion in the very first over. Burns though played well for his 57 but the Windies kept on chipping wickets. They had the upper hand in the first two sessions and had England at 122/4. But the pair who so far had struggled with the bat decided to find form at the right time for its side. The duo of Pope and Buttler steadied the ship and ensured that there was no more damage on Day 1. The pair has added an unbeaten 136-run stand with Pope on 91 and Buttler on 56. This has ensured that it is England who are in the driver's seat at the end of Day 1.

Back of a length delivery on middle, Buttler offers a solid defense on this one.
On a good length on off, Buttler defends it off the back foot.
On a good length and outside off, Buttler leaves it alone.
Good length delivery on off, Pope pushes it towards point for a single.
SIX! This is good batting from Jos Buttler! Tossed up delivery on middle, Buttler lofts it over long on for a biggie.
Full delivery on middle, Buttler drives it to mid on.
Loopy delivery on middle, Jos flicks it towards the leg side.
SIX! That is huge! Flighted delivery on middle, Buttler lofts it over mid-wicket for a maximum.
Floated delivery on middle, Buttler flicks it to mid-wicket.
Tossed up delivery on middle, Pope flicks it through square leg for a run.
Good length delivery on off, Buttler keeps it out.
On a length on off, Pope punches it through point for a run.
Full on off, Pope gets on his front foot and defends it.
Outside off, Pope has nothing to do with it.
Full outside off, Pope pushes it to cover.
Good length ball on off, Pope blocks it.
Tossed up delivery on middle, Pope drives it through mid on for a single.
Full delivery on middle, Pope drives it towards mid on.
Loopy delivery on off, Pope blocks it off the front foot.
Floated delivery on middle, Ollie flicks it to mid-wicket.
Flighted delivery on off, Pope defends it out.
Tossed up delivery on middle, Pope flicks it towards the leg side.
Rahkeem Cornwall is back on.
On a good length and outside off, Jos lets it go.
NO BALL! Jason Holder oversteps! On a good length on off, Buttler defends it off the back foot.
Good length delivery outside off, Buttler offers no shot to this one.
Good length delivery on off, Jos defends it off the back foot.
On a length on middle, Pope flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.
Outside off, Pope shoulders arms to this one.
Full delivery on middle, Buttler flicks it through mid-wicket. The batsmen get three runs.
FOUR! Another boundary and England are moving along. Full outside off, Pope is quick to get on his front foot and drive it through covers for a boundary.
On the leg side, Pope looks to flick it but then decides to leave it.
Full on off, Pope pushes it to mid off.
FOUR! Too wide and punished again by Pope. Fuller outside off, Pope drives it square on the off side, in the gap through backward point for a boundary.
Length ball around off, Buttler gets on his back foot and punches it through covers and gets three as the fielder cleans it up before the ropes.
Good length ball on off, Buttler defends it off his back foot.
On off, Pope blocks it.
Outside off, Pope leaves it alone.
On a good length on off, Ollie keeps it out.
Good length delivery on off, Pope defends it off the back foot.

FOUR! FIFTY FOR POPE. He gets to his half century in style. A very important innings for Pope and his side. He has been short of runs in this series but he has stood up when his side needed him the most. Full ball outside off, Pope gets on his front foot and drives it through covers to get to his fifty. He raises his bat as his teammates applaud his effort. Job not over yet as he needs to convert this into a big one.
On a good length and outside off, Buttler offers no shot to this one.
On off, Pope blocks it.
Down the leg side, Pope looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad.
FOUR! Poor ball and punished! Gabriel bowls it on the pads, Pope is quick to get on it and flick it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Fuller on off, Pope pushes it to mid off.

NOT OUT! Umpire's call on the bal hitting the stumps. Pope survives and West Indies also do not lose their review. Good length ball pitching around off and coming back n. Pope looks to defend but misses. The ball hits him over the knee roll.

FOUR! Excellent shot and Pope moves into his 40s with that. Fuller on off and it comes in with the angle. Pope gets on his front foot and keeps brilliant balance to hit it through mid on for a boundary.
On a good length and outside off, Jos shoulders arms to this one.
On a good length on off, Buttler defends it off the back foot.
Full delivery on middle, Pope drives it towards mid on for a single.
FOUR! Nicely played! Short and outside off, Pope cuts it between gully and point for a boundary.
Short delivery on middle, Buttler pulls it towards fine leg for a single.
Full delivery on middle, Pope flicks it through mid-wicket. The fielder chases it and does well to stop it before the ropes. The batsmen get three runs.
On a good length on middle, Buttler keeps it out.
Good length delivery on off, Jos blocks it off the front foot.
FOUR! Poor delivery from Gabriel! Short delivery on leg, Buttler pulls it towards fine leg for a boundary.
NO BALL! Gabriel oversteps! On a length on middle, Buttler flicks it to mid-wicket.

IN THE AIR...DROPPED! Excellent effort from Chase but he cannot take it. Harsh to call it a drop because he was always up against it and it was a terrific effort from him. Gabriel hits the deck hard and bowls it around the body of Pope. The ball comes in just around his belly. He looks to turn it on the leg side but gets a leading edge which goes high in the air behind mid-wicket. Chase runs behind from short mid-wicket and gives the catch a chase. He dives and gets his fingers to it but cannot hold onto it. Excellent effort from the all-rounder. Lucky escape for Pope. He should have played pull to that ball.
Good length delivery on off, Pope blocks it off the back foot.
On a good length on middle, Pope defends it off the back foot.
Another one away from the stumps, Buttler leaves it alone.
Away from the stumps, Buttler has nothing to do with it.
Length ball outside off, JB shoulders arms to it.
Outside off, Buttler leaves it alone and Dowrich manages to pouch it this time.

Oh poor Dowrich, he is struggling behind the stumps. Good length ball outside off, Pope leaves it alone. Dowrich behind the stumps misreads it and the ball goes towards third man after hitting his finger and allows the batters to get three byes.
Outside off, Pope shoulders arms to it.
FOUR! Gorgeous shot! Ah! What a delight! Holder overpitches it on off, Buttler gets on his front foot and plays a classical straight drive through mid off for a boundary.
Short ball down the leg side, Buttler ducks under it.
Good length ball outside off, it keeps going away. Buttler leaves it alone.
On middle and leg, Buttler flicks but finds short mid-wicket.
Full but down the leg side, Buttler looks to flick but misses.
Full on off, Buttler defends it off the front foot.
On a good length and outside off, Pope lets it go.
Full again on off, Pope drives it to mid off.
FOUR! Full delivery outside off, Pope looks to drive but gets an outside edge. It goes towards third man for a boundary.
On a good length and outside off, Pope leaves it alone.
Length delivery on off, Ollie plays it to covers.
BEATEN! On a good length and outside off, Pope looks to defend but misses it.
Good length delivery on off, Buttler blocks it off the back foot.
Full delivery on middle, Buttler flicks it to mid-wicket.
On a good length and outside off, Buttler shoulders arms to this one.
Good length delivery outside off, Jos offers no shot to this one.
Length delivery on off, Buttler punches it to covers.
On a good length and outside off, Buttler leaves it alone.
On middle and leg, Pope flicks it through mid-wicket and gets a couple as he gets off the mark for the session.

Edged but falls shot! Good length ball outside off, it is in the channel of uncertainty. Pope lunges forward and has a feel of the ball. The ball takes the outside edge and falls short of Holder at second slip.
On a good length on off, Pope blocks it off the back foot.
Short delivery on middle, Buttler pulls it through square leg for a run.
On a good length on off, Jos defends it off the back foot.
Good length delivery outside off, Buttler shoulders arms to this one.

It will be interesting to see how does Holder rotate his bowlers. 26 overs to go to the second new ball. So a quick burst here, around 5-10 overs and then a spin barrage till the second new cherry. They will not want to delay the second new ball here.
Kemar Roach to bowl from the other end.
Maiden to begin the new session. Good length ball on off, Ollie defends it to get through the over.
Full on off, Pope taps it back to Holder.
Slightly fuller and shaping away, Pope defends it from right under his eyeline.
Holder hits the deck hard on off, Pope gets on his back foot and dabs the ball down the ground.
Holder finds his line and bowls it on a length on off, Pope defends it off the front foot.
False start to the new session from Holder. He starts the final session with a delivery down the leg side. Pope looks to flick but it is too far away.

We are back for the final session of Day 1. The West Indies' players are out in the middle. Ollie Pope and Jos Buttler will resume their innings for England. Jason Holder will start the proceedings for the final session of Day 1.
... Day 1, Evening Session ...

So if you look at the overall run rate, it is under 2.5. West Indies are into England's soft underbelly of a middle order and will look to make inroads. How will Jos Buttler play? In a free-flowing manner? Can someone remind him of his knock against India a couple of summers ago? The game resumes at 4 pm local (1500 GMT).

The post-Lunch session started with West Indies coming out firing on all cylinders. Stokes was hit on the helmet and then a couple of balls later, was dismissed. Then, Pope got one on the helmet and hence, the batsmen were finding it uncomfortable. Rory Burns looked good and set, but could not carry on, thanks to a blinder from Rahkeem Cornwall at slip.

65/2 in 26 overs in this session. Jason Holder will be thrilled with the control his bowlers have showed in this passage. They had a control over the run rate and hence, did not let England run away in what is normally termed as a session for the batsmen.
Wide outside off, just holds its line, doesn't swing back in, good from Buttler as he doesn't chase that. Leaves it through. TEA ON DAY 1!
Outside off, kept out watchfully to the off side. A quick single taken.
Fuller in length, around off, flicked towards deep mid-wicket for a single.
Around off, watchfully defended.

Umm... leaving? Playing? Perhaps caught in two minds. On a length outside off, Buttler looks to defend initially but then thinks to let the ball go. Is late and the bat is left hanging in the air. Luckily for him, the ball hits the good spot of the willow and goes on the bounce to the slip cordon.
Around off, tucked through mid-wicket for a single.
Last over? Yep. Last one before Tea. Kemar Roach is the bowler. 11.4-1-26-2 so far.
Wider outside off, let through again.
Fuller in length, outside off, watchfully defended.
Outside off, left alone.
Fuller this time, well defended.
Around off, solidly defended.

WOULD POPE HAVE BEEN A GONER? Dear me, he would have been! On middle, Ollie pushes it towards mid on and sets off for a single. It is Roston Chase at short mid-wicket who ambles towards the ball, stoops to pick the ball up and at that time, Pope is gone for all money. Because he is just halfway down the track. But, just when he is about to flick the ball with his left hand, he fumbles the ball and it pops out. What a relief for Ollie Pope.
Landed outside off, on a length, Jos shoulders arms.
Outside off, pushed through the covers for a single.
Back of a length, outside off, Ollie hops and defends.

Poor shot and poor keeping again. Seems like a loss in confidence for Dowrich. Full and wide outside off, Pope looks at that and cannot resist himself. Throws the kitchen sink at it, looking to drive but misses. Shane Dowrich looks to collect to his right, but struggles against the wobbly seam. Fumbles.
Outside off, pushed towards point.

Na na... not what Holder or Gabriel had in mind. He needed the new man on strike. He looks back at the pitch, as if to indicate something to do with his landing. Full and fast yes, but straying down the leg side. Buttler tickles it towards fine leg for a single.
A length ball, outside off, Pope gets across and shoulders arms.
A length ball, around off, OP defends it watchfully.
Full and down the leg side, Ollie misses his flick.
Full and outside off, Pope pushes this through the covers and gets a couple.
On a length outside off, Ollie is solid in defense again.
Full and around off, Pope defends it watchfully.
Jason Holder is back on. 10-3-22-0 so far. This time, things happened slowly enough for me to catch the change in bowling. Cheap happiness stuff...
Around off, defended watchfully this time.
A length ball, outside off, Jos looks to defend but the ball cuts back in, rises steeply, makes Buttler hop, takes the inside edge and hits him on the pads.
Another bouncer, the result is the same.
A bouncer now, Buttler ducks.

The wobbly seam is troubling Shane Dowrich again. He was all at sea in the second Test and being on the field for a long time did not assist him. A length ball, outside off, Ollie lets it go. The ball wobbles off the seam and then moves in a long way. Dowrich struggles to collect and fumbles, conceding a bye.
Around off, pushed towards point.
Around middle, worked towards short mid-wicket.
How did that miss the off stump? Full and flighted outside off, Buttler looks to drive but the ball spins in, goes beneath the bat and goes over the off stump!
Into the list of batsmen who have not done too well with the bat in this series. First up, Jos Buttler.

OUT! CAUGHT! Sir Andrew Strauss, Chase heard you! And dear Cornwall, what a catch! What a catch! Will come back to that Strauss comment later. First, the ball. Short and outside off, Burns rocks back to cut but is too close to the ball. He gets a thick outside edge as a result and the ball flies thick and fast to first slip. The giant Rahkeem Cornwall there, has barely any time to react but he trusts his instincts. He just thrusts his right hand and the ball sticks! Tremendous reflexes. Chase is ringing the bells again, as his celebration suggests. Now, about the Strauss comment. Sir Andrew Strauss on air, felt that after including an extra spinner in your side, you should not be bowling first. He was just saying 'Hmmmm...' pondering over something else to say when Chase struck. Poor from Burns. Should have carried on!
Rory comes down the track and pushes it towards mid on.
Around middle, watchfully defended.
Full and outside off, Burns reaches out and drives it towards cover.
Full and around off, driven back to the bowler.
Wild. Ill-directed. Full and miles down the leg side, Pope tries his best to flick. Misses. Shane Dowrich dives to his left to collect.
Around middle and leg, helped through square leg for one more.
A short ball, around off, pulled through square leg for a single.

Michael Holding has observed Shannon Gabriel bowling short stuff to Rory Burns. While he approves the idea of the length, he just wants the batsman to be changed. Meaning, he wants Gabriel to bowl more short stuff to Pope and fuller to Burns.
A short ball, around off, Pope lets it go.
A length ball, outside off, solidly defended.
Gabriel is smiling. Not sure why. Kemar Roach has the ball in his hand at mid off. Now, he throws it to Gabriel. Must have been some joke.
Short and outside off, Rory goes back and cuts it towards point.
Full and around off, Pope comes down the track and flicks it uppishly, wide of short mid-wicket, for a single.
Goes right back in his crease and defends.
Ohhh... I missed it! Roston Chase is bowling. When nothing seemingly happens, then some things get missed out...
Around off, OP blocks it out again.
Fired in, outside off, Ollie defends watchfully.
Full and around off, Pope defends this solidly.
Outside off, left alone.
A bouncer now, on middle, Burns ducks under it.
A bit too straight, flicked away for a single.
Outside off, left alone.

That is a jaffa. On a length outside off, Pope looks to defend but the ball comes back in a long way and nearly shaves the off stump. Ollie thought he had it covered but the ball exposed the tiniest of gaps between bat and pad.
Full and around middle and off, Pope works it through mid-wicket and gets a couple.
Outside off, punched off the back foot, through point for a couple.
Around off, well defended.
Floated outside off, Ollie comes down the track and pushes it to the leg side for a single.
Around middle, defended solidly.
FOUR! That is a solid shot. Full and outside off, Pope comes down the track and flicks it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Back of a length, outside off, watchfully defended.
On a good length, defended watchfully.
Full and just outside off, well defended.
Beaten! Excellent from Gabriel. Full and around leg, Burns looks to defend but the ball pitches and then moves away off the seam to beat the outside edge.
Down the leg side, left alone.
A short ball, outside off, Burns slashes hard but gets a bottom edge. The ball bounces in front of the keeper.
A length ball, outside off, Pope stays back and defends. The ball rolls to the off side and the batsmen take a single.
Around middle again, Burns goes back and blocks.
Around middle, pushed to the leg side.
Looped up, around off, Rory stretches out to defend.
Full and around off, watchfully blocked out.
Fuller and straighter, watchfully defended.
FOUR! Bit of a gift after the break. Short and outside off, easy for feasting and Burns feasts. Rocks back and cuts it through the covers.

Burns is batting superbly but he now needs to take extra responsibility. The next man in is Buttler and then, come the all-rounders. And Jos Buttler, is not in the best of form. Hence, a wicket here and it could be a procession. Rory needs to take guard of that. Cornwall to continue. A slip, a short leg and a very straight mid on, in fact a silly mid on, right in the non-striker's face. Jason Holder it is.

DRINKS BREAK. An hour into the session. Whose has it been? West Indies' for sure. 38 runs, for the wicket of the big Ben Stokes. The consistency in lengths has been lacking but the bowling has been decent. There were a few questions asked regarding the approach of England's batting earlier. You are going to lose pretty much the whole of tomorrow and Day 5. How about playing some strokes and lifting the run rate? Not a fan of that personally. Especially in Tests. Play your natural game, let the situation take care of itself. The weather is not in anyone's control.
Full and around off, pushed towards mid on.
7th Test Fifty for Rory Burns! It has been a good start for him in this Test. But now is the main part. Make use of this start.
Comes around the wicket, does Gabriel, dishes it into the ribs, but Burns tucks it towards fine leg for a single.
There comes the response from the fast bowler. I am no military medium guy, so better don't step out! A bumper, a sharp one at that, around leg, Burns is forced to duck. Try walking into that one...

This time Burns walks into the stroke. Normally, batsmen do this to negate the swing. There isn't any but this is just Burns' habit. Every now and then, he will step out. This is pushed towards mid on.

One of my colleagues has a good insight into the Ben Stokes' dismissal! He opines that Ben was standing outside the crease and Roach pushed him back by bowling a few well-directed bumpers. That made a bit of a doubt in Stokes' mind regarding the lengths and voila!
Fullish and around off, pushed towards cover.
On a good length, around off, well pushed to the off side.
He is back! Shannon Gabriel, that is. We are informed that he has bowled on every single day of this series where we have had play. Yet, he is playing all the three Tests!
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.
Flatter outside off, watchfully kept out.

Fuller and pushed towards point. Chase is the fielder again and England think about the single and get it. Hang on. Here is the reason. While fielding the ball, Chase got an extra bounce. Hence fumbled. That would have stung him on his arm.
Shorter, outside off, played straight to point.

Now Pope comes down the track and works it through mid-wicket. Poor fielding from Roston Chase. He ambles after the ball and the batsmen spot that. There is a fumble as well near the ropes and the batsmen take the third on the throw.
Full and outside off, not much pace, watchfully defended.
Aahhh... nearly! Full and miles wide outside off, Burns almost goes after it. The thought is there for the drive but then, he bails out, at the last moment. The slip cordon is cheering on Roach.
Fractionally shorter than full, outside off, but a touch wide. RB lets it pass.
Full and outside off again, but this time Rory gets across and pokes it into the leg side. Towards mid-wicket where there is a yawning gap. Easy couple taken.
There comes the sucker ball. Full and outside off. Asking to be driven. Is driven, but with proper footwork. Straight to cover.
Another bouncer, this time to a different batsman. Burns ducks under it calmly.

The physio is out again, to check for concussion signs. Pope looks just a touch dazzled. Looks at his helmet and finally, the smile comes out. Must have been on some question asked by the physio. Nice. He looks fine. Good to continue.

Another one on the helmet. The umpire is in Pope's ears. Excellent short ball from Roach. This is around off, Ollie looks to pull but is beaten by pace. The ball rockets onto the helmet and then deflects towards square leg. A leg bye taken.
Interesting stance from Pope in that last Cornwall over. Covered all his stumps, then walked across.
Decent shot. Quicker one, fired in with the arm, Pope goes back and punches it past first slip. That fielder himself has to run all the way towards third man. John Campbell it is. Three runs taken.
The use of the feet again. Pope dances out and works it towards short mid-wicket.
Similar ball, same defensive stroke from Pope.
Flatter, around off, Ollie goes back to block again.
Around off, Pope comes down the track and pushes it towards short mid-wicket.
Full and outside off, watchfully blocked out.
A fine ball to end the over. Fullish and just straightening a touch, RB defends it watchfully. A maiden over but really not of much use from Roach. A bit too wayward.
Dozing! There are less people on the ground these days. And of those, the cameraman spots a lad with his sunglasses on, but dozing. Too much for him. Must have had a heavy lunch.
On a length, outside off, moving away, shouldered arms to.
Fuller in length, around off, well kept out.
Outside off, Burns watchfully lets it go. This was a lot closer than the previous one.
That is a shocker. Full and miles outside off, Rory does not even need to play that. Nearly outside the pitch! Roach is letting away some momentum go.
Easy. Just too easy. New man, get a straight ball. What do I need to do? Flick it away and I am underway. A single to square leg.

One can just sense some change in momentum. Since Lunch. The fielders look a bit more charged up. And then, from nowhere, Stokes got out. Good chance for West Indies to expose this soft underbelly of a middle order.
Full and straight, well blocked out. Nice complimenting over from Cornwall. Nothing adventurous. This means Roach will have the new man on strike.
Oohhh... a bit aerial, but just wide of short leg! Full and on the pads, Rory looks to flick but gets it off the inner half. Just past short leg!
Aha... use of the feet. Burns dances down and pushes it towards mid on.
Less flight this time, around off, pushed to the off side.
Faster, around middle, tucked straight to short leg again.
Full to begin with, around off, Burns blocks it in front of short leg.
Who's in next? West Indies seamers are on fire here. England need a good partnership here. Ollie Pope has come in.

OUT! BOWLED! Stokes stands in disbelief. What happened? A ball has gone through the gate. Massive gap between bat and pad. Kaboom! On a length, just outside off, Stokes looks to defend but a bit lazily. There is no foot movement but the ball moves. There is a big gap between bat and pad and the ball finds that. Off and middle pegs hit. Stokes is a goner!
Full and wide outside off, the tempter, left alone.
Good length ball, watchfully defended.
FOUR! No stopping that. Short ball but Ben is ready. Camps back and pulls it with disdain through mid-wicket. Bring 'em on!
We have a slight delay. The physio is out, as is the norm, when the ball hits the batsman. Stokes looks to be in some sort of pain.

HOWZZAT? Nope, says the umpire. Roach is not sure. Jason Holder asks his slip fielders and his keeper. No one is sure either. So no review. A short ball, around off, Stokes looked to pull but was hurried into the shot. Extra pace from Roach. The ball went off something to the keeper and there was a noise. There was a mild appeal but nothing much in it. The ball hit the helmet.
On a length, around middle, Stokes rises with the bounce and pushes it to the leg side.
A proper solid backfoot defense, as the over ends.
Full once more, nicely tossed up, pushed back watchfully.
Around middle, Stokes goes back and works it to the leg side for a single.
Going on the back foot this time, working it behind square on the leg side for one more.
Comes down the track this time, gets to the pitch of the ball and blocks.
Rahkeem Cornwall is back on.
Full and outside off, Burns goes back and pushes it towards cover.
Once again Roach delivers it on middle and leg, closer to Burns' body and this time he glances it behind square on the leg side and keeps the strike with a single.
On the pads, Rory turns it to the on side.
Fuller on off, Burns blocks it.
On the body, Stokes turns it to the on side and gets to the other end.
Full on off, Stokes defends it a bit late so the ball bounces around him and hits him on his back pad.
Good length delivery on the body, Stokes tucks it to the leg side.
Fuller on off, Burns defends it.
Fuller on off, Stokes plays it to mid off and takes a single.
Another short ball, Burns pulls it through mid-wicket. The fielder stops the ball before the ropes and saves a run.
Bouncer on the body, Stokes pulls it through mid-wicket and gets a single
Fuller on off, Stokes pushes through covers and gets a couple.
Outside off, Stokes leaves it alone.
Good length delivery outside off, Rory shoulders arms to this one.
Roach bowls a bouncer, Burns does well to duck under it.
On a good length on off, Rory defends it off the front foot.
Full delivery on off, Burns drives it through covers. The batsmen pick up a couple.
Full delivery on middle, Burns drives it towards mid on.
Outside off, Burns lets it go.
On a good length on off, Ben defends it off the back foot.
Good length delivery outside off, Stokes leaves it alone.
Length delivery on middle, Stokes flicks it through square leg. The batsmen get two runs.
Outside off, Ben shoulders arms to this one.
Yayyyyy! Gabriel is back on the field and he is stretching!
Good length delivery on off, Stokes defends it off the back foot.
On a good length and outside off, Stokes offers no shot to this one.
Full delivery on middle, Burns plays it to mid on.
Full delivery on middle, Burns looks to drive but gets it off the inner half of the bat. It goes towards mid-wicket.
Good length delivery outside off, Burns shoulders arms to this one.
BEATEN! Full delivery outside off, Rory looks to drive but misses it.
Full delivery on middle, Burns drives it towards mid on.
On a length on middle, Stokes flicks it through square leg for a run.
Kemar Roach will bowl from the other end.
Length delivery on off, Burns gets on his front foot and drives it through covers and gets a couple to end the over.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
On a good length on middle, Burns looks to defend but gets hit on the thigh pad.
On a good length on off, Burns looks to defend but gets an outside edge. It falls short of the gully fielder.
Full delivery on off, Burns drives it towards mid off.

FOUR! The new session starts with a boundary! Holder starts with a loosener as he bowls a length delivery outside off. Burns gets on his back foot and punches it through backward point for a boundary.

Cannot see Shannon Gabriel anywhere. Not that my eyesight is the best, but given that the population these days on a cricket ground is fairly less, it is easier to spot players. That will be a concern for West Indies. Not my spotting, Gabriel's absence...
We are back for the second session. The West Indies players are out in the middle. Rory Burns and Ben Stokes will resume their innings for England.
... Day 1, Session 2 ...

West Indies, on the other hand, will look to build on the first session and unlike the last game keep chipping away at wickets regularly. Who will the second session belong to? Join us at 1340 local (1240 GMT) for the second session.

A good session  for the tourists and they have justified Holder's decision to bowl first at least in the first session. They got rid of last Test's marathon man, Dom Sibley early on. Root and Burns were weathering the storm before Chase's brilliant effort in the field ended the 46-run stand. Ben Stokes and Burns though ensured there were no more casualties before the end of the first session. England will hope Burns and their messiah, Ben Stokes take them out of troubled waters and help them put on a big score.
On a length on middle, Burns flicks it through square leg for a single. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 1!
On a good length on off, Burns looks to defend  but gets an outside edge. It goes safely towards third man. The fielder chases it and does well to stop it. The batsmen get two runs.
Bouncer on leg, Burns does well to duck under it.
Gabriel again bowls a bumper, Rory ducks under it.
Gabriel bowls a bouncer, Burns does well to duck under it.
Length delivery down the leg side, Burns looks to flick but misses it.
On middle, Stokes defends it out.
FOUR! Nice use of the feet! Tossed up delivery on middle, Stokes comes down the track and drives it through mid on for a boundary.
On middle, Ben offers a solid defense on this one.
Loopy delivery on off, Stokes defends it off the back foot.
Flighted delivery on middle, Stokes blocks it off the back foot.
Tossed up delivery on off, Stokes keeps it out.
Length delivery on middle, Stokes flicks it towards square leg for a run.
On a good length on off, Ben blocks it off the back foot.
Good length delivery outside off, Stokes offers no shot to this one.
In the air but safe! Short ball around the body, Burns looks to pull but mistimes it and it goes high in the air. Luckily for him it falls short of the man coming from fine leg.
On a good length on off, Burns defends it off the back foot.
A bouncer now, on middle, Burns ducks.
The batsman defends it from within the crease.

OUT! Run Out! Excellent work in the field from and Root who was getting in his groove has to depart. Big wicket for the tourists and a big blow for Enngland. Back-to-back run out for Joe Root. Hello and a warm welcome to the our coverage of the final Test match of the series between England and West Indies. It has all come to a decider after 2 terrific Test matches, and this one promises to be another cracker. England have plenty of selection headaches regarding their bowlers, but it is a good headache to have considering the options that Root has to call upon. West Indies, on the other hand, would need to decide if they want to rest some of their bowlers and give someone else a chance. There have been noise from the outside to include Rahkeem Cornwall in the starting XI and by doing that, bringing in a specialist spinner. In the batting department, they need Shai Hope as well to come back to form. The forecast has not been great for this Test, with rain predicted on all 5 days. Let's hope it stays away. Join us in a while for the toss and further updates.
Here come the two English openers. 20 minutes to bat.

Less than 20 minutes to go for Lunch. England are well ahead in this game but in personal terms, this will be a nervous moment for Rory Burns and Dom Sibley. They would want to go into the break unscathed.

Another shoddy display with the bat for the visitors. This time it has been technical deficiency which has brought about their downfall. Playing from the crease, not shuffling their feet and getting trapped by the movement of the ball. Only Jason Holder played an innings of some confidence while the rest simply withered away. Dowrich's innings looks good on the scorecard but he struggled for a major part while Campbell got a brute.

So West Indies avoid the follow-on but England get a lead of 172. That is more than enough for a result if we get one full day's play. The bowling was pretty much upto the mark, except for that first hour this morning. 6 wickets for Broad, 2 for Anderson, but the entire bowling unit was excellent.

Stuart Broad takes the ball from Woakes and rightly so. He will want to keep that to himself. Not selected for the first Test and he has definitely made his point. 6 wickets in 14 overs, that is a wicket every 14 balls.

WEATHER - A look at the heavens will bring smiles on all the faces of cricket fans. Dry in Manchester, no rain as of now.

All eyes would be on Jason Holder this morning. If his team can manage to bat this whole session, that deficit could come down to around 150. Still huge, but England would have to bat that much while longer to set a target of 400 or more.

To be honest, West Indies cannot depend on the weather. They are so far behind in this game, that just one full day's play can finish this match off. First, they need to score those 33 runs to avoid the follow-on and if they do, try and delay the inevitable by bowling tightly. But eventually, when they do get to bat, they have to play out of their skins, which is extremely difficult in the final innings.

So - why do we say will the Windies question the heavens? Because as per the forecast, there shouldn't have been much play yesterday. But we nearly had a full day's play! The forecast is for lesser showers today but if the forecast for 90 percent rain on Saturday did not prove right, what are the chances that the forecast for today will?

Another day in this Test match with West Indies having their backs to the wall. After the first game, such situations have occurred regularly in these two Tests. And now, having entered a Test with rain forecast for a major portion, the tourists find themselves questioning the heavens. Hello and a warm welcome to the third day of this third Test between England and West Indies in Manchester.

Okay then! We weren't supposed to stay up so late, were we? But for a change, the forecast in England proved to be false! We nearly had a full day's play with England probably just another full day's play away from winning this match and series. Join us on Sunday, 26th July, 2020 at 11 am local (1000 GMT) for all the action from Day 3. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

The other English bowlers took inspiration from Broad. Especially Anderson, who came out all guns blazing. The tourists just could not find any breathing space and twice in two games, they are waiting with bated breath to see if some saviour bails them out of follow-on embarrassment.

Bowlers generally do well when they have had a lovely time with the bat. The Stuart Broad England loves, is back. The flashing of the blade, the pulling, the cutting, the driving - what not? And then he struck immediately with the ball too.

How did this all happen? The tourists began the day really well, getting 4 English wickets for just 18 runs, before Stuart Broad came in their way. Somehow, that 9th wicket partnership between Broad and Bess put West Indies off their track. From 280/8, the hosts managed to reach 369.
Right! So where were we? England on top at the end of Day 1. Where are we? England on top at the end of Day 2. First, with the bat. Then, with the ball. West Indies are in all sorts of disarray.

Heartening to hear the conversation between Ebony Rainford Brent and Michael Holding on air. For the record, Holding finished his Test career with 249 Test wickets. On being asked by Ebony as to how does he feel on not being able to touch 250, Mikey says that he does not feel anything, as 250 is just a number. He further adds that plenty of people ask him whether he could have played more games to get to 250 but he curtly says ,'No, thank you!' Ebony tries to convince him that it could have perhaps been just one more game but Holding serenely replies - 'If it is a win for West Indies, then 250 is better than 249. Else not.' So that is it from the Wisden Trophy. Cricket came back after a break of more than 100 days and it came back with a very good fighting series but England showed their superiority and came back to win the series 2-1. Holder and co. showed fight but it was not enough in the end. A lot of positives to take and work with moving forward for the Caribbean nation. England now will welcome Ireland for a 3-match ODI series which will also kickstart the ICC World ODI Super League. Thanks for joining us for the coverage. Hope you enjoyed it as much as we did. Until next time, goodbye and take care!

England skipper, Joe Root, tells that the last two weeks have been excellent and says they have been able to execute their plans that they had in the last two games. On his ambitions, he says he never set any target but tells he has learnt a lot and feels fresh and has worked on his techincal game and says he is looking forward for the future. Stay tuned as we wait for the captain's thoughts and also find out who the Man of the Match and Player of the Series are. A fair few contenders for the latter as we have had some very good performance by a few players in this series.

Stuart Broad had a Test to remember and he was in the mood to punish the Caribbean side. For the hosts, they needed weather to help them out but nature by itself could not do anything if they were unable to fight for themselves. They lost 2 wickets towards the end of Day 3 as Broad was spitting venom. Rain did give West Indies a little bit of hope as Day 4 was washed out but the tourists had lost the game in their head and showed little to no resistance as Broad added 2 more to his 2 from Day 3 and finished the Test with 10 wickets to add to his important fifty from the first innings and the consistency of Woakes saw him grab a 5-fer in the second innings to hand England a dominant win.

England then were always in a position to win it and it was going to take a miracle or English weather to avoid them a win. Building on their lead, the opening pair of Sibley and Burns took their time and batted the tourists out of the game with their fifties. Skipper Joe Root then came out after the dismissal of Sibley and his ODI-esque added impetus to the innings and ballooned that lead to 398 before Burns departed for 90 and the skipper decided they had enough. West Indies bowling struggled as Gabriel bowled just 5 overs and they had surrendered.

Momentum was with England and Broad and they carried it to the field as a brilliant display of seam bowling as they never let West Indies settle and chipped wickets regularly and bundled them to just 197 and carried a 172 runs lead. Stuart Broad was the tormentor in cheif as he grabbed a 6-wicket haul. The West Indies batting struggled and no one got going. The only saving grace for them was that they avoided the follow-on but apart from that there was nothing much to write about them with only skipper Holder and Dowrich showing some fight.

End of a fantastic Test series and England after being 1-0 down have shown their grit and strength to win the series 2-1. A very dominant performance from the hosts with both the bat and ball. West Indies showed a lot of promise at the beginning of the tour but with every Test and passing day in those Tests, they looked tired and their fight started to surrender. After being put into bat, the hosts were in a state of bother at 122/4 but a brilliant 140-run stand between Pope and Buttler along with Broad's counter-attacking 62 propelled them to 369. Kemar Roach was the pick of the bowlers for the hosts as he finished the first innings with a 4-fer.

Hope's struggle in the longest format continues and there will be a lot of questions asked and he will have to retrospect and think, was that shot really necessary?

OUT! LBW! Broad enters the galaxy of greats and he has his 500th Test wicket. Brathwaite three years ago was Anderson's 500th wicket and now he has become his partner Broad's milestone victim. Proud moment for Broad, his friends and family. Broad bowls goes fuller on off, the ball comes back in and also keeps low after pitching. Brathwaite looks to defend but misses and gets hit low on the back foot. Broad and his teammates go up in appeal and the umpire raises his finger. That was as plumb as It could get and Brathwaite has a rare double. 583 balls left in the day, 7 wickets to defend...

Yippeee! We are all set for the final day of the Wisden Trophy, 2020 and the final day of the Trophy in general. The players are on the field on a day which is cold and blustery. West Indies need to show some character. Here is Jimmy Anderson from the Jimmy Anderson end to Kraigg Brathwaite.

Stuart Broad probably would have spent a couple of nights sleeplessly thinking about his to-be 500th Test victim while Kraigg Brathwaite would be hoping, or rather aiming, NOT to be that 500th victim. He was Anderson's 500th Test victim as well, at Lord's, in September 2017!

WEATHER - A look at the heavens straight up. There was a passing shower around 30 minutes ago but now, the ground is bathed in sunshine. We could have a prompt start but that depends on how wet or dry the ground is. We are expecting intermittent showers throughout the day, but can guarantee you enough action to enjoy.

98 overs, 8 wickets. That is the equation. Not many would be really bothered about chasing down 389, unless you are Sir Viv Richards or Ricky Ponting. England looking for the series, West Indies aiming for survival while fans hoping for some cricket. Hello and a warm welcome to this final day of the Wisden Trophy.

West Indies will be happy. They have been given a lifeline. It is now to try and bat out the whole of Tuesday. Even in that, they have hope of having around a session to be washed out. Will England have enough time to claim the series and the last edition of the Wisden Trophy? Join us on 28th July, 2020 at 11 am local (1000 GMT). ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

Good night! Nothing, absolutely nothing could make play happen in Manchester on Monday. Incessant rain has forced DAY 4 TO BE CALLED OFF. The weather was clearing but given that more wet weather was forecast around 5 pm (1600 GMT), the umpires have taken the safety call.

1448 GMT - It should have been the time when Tea is taken in Manchester. But unfortunately, nothing much has changed from the last update. If any, the rain has gotten heavier. We may not be far from shutting the shop.
There we go. It has started to RAIN. Forget that inspection now...

1259 GMT - The umpires are taking an inspection. There are puddles developed on the outfield and if I am a good face-reader, then those emotions certainly don't reckon that they are happy one bit. We are hearing that there is an INSPECTION SCHEDULED AT 3 PM LOCAL (1400 GMT). Of course, if there is no more rain.

1243 GMT - Rain has stopped. Take a breath. Now read again. Rain has stopped. But the covers look absolutely wet. It is going to take a real long time to drain the water out. Our fear is - the groundstaff does all the hard work, only for the rain to come and wash away all its efforts. Poor blokes.

1206 GMT - It would have been Lunch in normal scenarios, as it would have been time for a break. But we have been having a break ever since the last ball was bowled last evening. Not much comfortable updates on the weather, with a grim forecast looming.

England's ODI squad for Ireland series - Eoin Morgan(c), Moeen Ali, Jonny Bairstow, Tom Banton, Sam Billings, Tom Curran, Liam Dawson, Joe Denly, Saqib Mahmood, Adil Rashid, Jason Roy, Reece Topley, James Vince and David Willey.

With two days officially remaining in this match and the series, it is time to look beyond. Pakistan play England next, but before that, Ireland have a little peek-a-boo for a 3-ODI series. England have just announced their squad for that series.

1100 GMT - Time for Drinks, gentlemen! Missing these words? Sadly, everyone is having a drink at the moment, but in the dressing room. The situation might have improved by just a little bit with the groundstaff hurrying across to mop but it does look like they will need plenty of time to dry this outfield. Only to see it get wet by another shower, as per the forecast.
An update on Shane Dowrich. He got hit on the chin yesterday while trying to keep. There is a little cut on the lip but no excessive damage. So he should be fit enough to bat.

Nothing much to update. Thought we might talk about the World Cup Super League. That is similar to the World Test Championship, only this will be for white-ball cricket. England and Ireland kickstart that series from 30th July, which will also see the TV umpire call front-foot no balls.

1000 GMT - The first ball is about to be bowled! This should have been our text by now. But unfortunately, we are nowhere even close to have play underway. First, rain has to stop. Then, the outfield has to dry. We are hearing about a brief passage of clear sky in the afternoon, but that will be followed by a thunderstorm prediction in the evening.

At times like these, our minds go back to the ground coverage in Sri Lanka. The groundsmen there cover the entire ground. That way, once the rain stops, it becomes easier to dry the ground out. Here, in the UK, once the rain stops, we have to spend extra time in drying the ground out. Well, human labour is costly in the UK and secondly, the drainage is pretty good in England.

Coming to this game, West Indies look almost buried. Giving a lead of 172, then being set a target of 399 and further, losing 2 wickets quickly. The prospect of Monday getting washed out might come as a relief for them but there is a Day 5 awaiting as well. If play resumes, how much time will England need to pick 8 wickets?
WEATHER - A look at the heavens first up. Not promising at all. It is soggy and the pitch is covered. Now, a look at the radar. Very threatening. It does seem like we might have a forced day-off...

Rain, rain, more rain. Come, so that West Indies might have some gain. Don't come so that fans may not have any more pain! Ahh... just as we thought that we might escape the weather in this Test, here comes the effect. Hello and a warm welcome, err... wet welcome to this fourth day of this third Test.

Thank you so much for joining the coverage of Day 3. Join us on Monday, Day 4 of the final Test between England and West Indies. The action will begin at 1100 local (1000 GMT). Hope to see you then. Till then, goodbye and take care!

So that is it from Day 3! West Indies are on the brink of surrendering the Wisden Trophy and only a miracle can see them bat 2 days or win this. The weather forecast for Day 4 does not look great which can be a good news if you support the Caribbean nation. Let's hope we have no rain and we can have play.

They missed their star man Shannon Gabriel with the ball as he bowled just 5 overs and they never looked like threatening the English batters. Their heads started to fall in the field and they looked completely opposite to how they looked in the first Test. Needing 399 to win and 2 days and 20 odd minutes to survive the first thing they would have wanted was to have their 10 wickets intact coming to Day 4 but they lost opener John Campbell and night watchman Kemar Roach. They are up against it and are in no place to save this Test.
A miserable day of cricket for West Indies. Everything started going downhill post the first hour. They looked tired, jaded, out of ideas and their bodies started to crumble.

Excellent day of cricket if you are an England fan but if you're a West Indian then it was just too painful. The tourists started off the day positively and avoided the follow-on in the first hour but after that it was all England. They bowled out West Indies for 197 and then the batting trio of Sibley, Burns and Root took the game to the depleted West Indies side who had a lot of fitness issues. They managed to build on the lead and decided to declare, giving the tourists 399 to chase. The hosts were so much in command that in the last 20 odd minutes the tourists had to bat, they managed to pick up 2 wickets with both falling to Broad.

OUT! Caught! Broad gets his 498th Test victim and that comes from a beauty! Traditional Broad wicket. He has enjoyed bowling to left-handers and has more often than not won the battle against them. Nothing different here. Terrific delivery from Broad. He comes in and bowls it slightly fuller on off, Campbell thinks it will come with the angle but goes the other way. It takes the fat outside edge of his willow and goes straight to first slip. Skipper, Joe Root there makes no mistake and takes a relatively easy catch. Just the start England would have wanted. Nightmare beginning to the chase for the Caribbean nation.
